title: E3D Chimera and Cyclops compact X-Carriage for Prusa i3 Style printers

description.text:
A minimalistic and light weight replacement X-Carriage for Prusa i3 style printers. The hotend is mounted high on the carriage to allow for the grub/set screws to be accessed from behind and to maximise build hight. The slim light weight design should help to maximise print speeds. A full assembly guide using this carriage is included on the E3D wiki:
http://wiki.e3d-online.com/wiki/Cyclops/Chimera_on_Prusa_i3 This carriage was inspired by a number of other designs, but remodelled from scratch.

Print with 50% infill in PLA or ABS (use ABS if you are going to do a lot of high temperature extrusion)  
It prints without supports, but I recommend printing with a brim to ensure that there is no warp.   
Clean up any stringing after printing before use.  
I found PLA works fine for me.

This little holder enables your phone to record 3D !!  
Put it over the lens on the phone and attach two mirrors in the slots (orange mirrors in the image) mirrors can be purchased from hobby and maker shops.. a larger size might work better..  
Then record a video where you adjust the screen to see a split screen, one half recording through the mirror, the other records directly what you point at.   
Then watch the video using VR goggles on the phone

comments.text:
Thanks for the comments!
yes, exactly, two cams using one.. -I got the idea from a very complicated thing from Kickstarter.. This one is quite a bit more simple- well you still need to get mirrors and lenses for the VR glasses, if you don't already have some..
And yes sure ;) I will make another small movie tomorrow and post it,. then maybe it will be easy to see without lenses on a larger monitor than the phone.
-The problem I still have is that the mirrors are not so large.

Please use only under direct supervision. 3D printed PLA has not been tested for cohesion or stability under continuous saliva exposure. If the material begins to break down or the color seems to be running, diminishing, or leaching out, please discontinue use. Take care in inspecting the toy before and after each use to determine the structural condition of the unit, and discontinue use if it begins to degrade. By downloading this design, you take all responsibility and liability for any resultant problems or damages.  Possible side effects include permanent injury and death.

Print the ninjaball first (or at the same time), then pause the print sometime when there's enough space to drop it into the rattle.  
The handle should be facing up, no support required though a brim might be necessary depending on the quality of your adhesion.  Ninjaball still needs to be rotated 90 degrees (X axis works) and then no supports required.

This is a clock design made from scrap laser-cut wood from a bunch of the Makerbots I had to cut for batch 3 and 4. The good thing about laser-cutting is that even the scrap has a digital design file that can be shared. 
I joined the pieces together with small clips I printed on my Makerbot. The clips are actually really great and I\'m definitely going to do more with them in the future. They\'re designed to snap onto 5mm (.25\") material and they do a good job of securing it in place.
I could have (and probably should have) printed the clips with the 30 degree angle needed built in to minimize trying to get everything aligned perfectly but I like the flexibility they have now.
TO DO: get a more aesthetically pleasing wall mounting. It looks okay and works well for now but I eventually want to print something to cover up the annoying metal hook on the back of the mechanism.

Laser cut 12 wood panel\'s and 1 square covering
Print 12 small woodclips and 12 long wood clips You'll probably want to draw out some sort of reference to get them to the proper angles so everything lines up. I used this clock mechanism (http://tinyurl.com/ktadq3) and it seems to work quite well (and it's very quiet which was very much a necessity for me). Snap everything together and enjoy!

title: ZMR250 mount for Sony Mini 600TVL camera

description.text:
Mounting the Sony Mini 600TVL camera on a ZMR250 is a challenge. The original mounting holes on the sides of the camera will strip out if the camera is hit ever so lightly. Likely on the first test flight. The next mounting alternative is to use threaded plastic rings around the lens and mount the camera through a holder. There are a few that can be found here:
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:725352
My front plastic ring stripped out after only a few flights, so I cancelled that idea. Instead I constructed a mount that is held in place by the front posts. The camera is then strapped in place by a thin zip tie.
The mount can be mounted on either the top or bottom frame plate.
An added advantage is that it becomes possible to remove the camera by just cutting the zip tie and loosening the two front posts, which is a lot easier than pulling the frame apart, which is needed for the other mounting options.
